Multi-Stage Docker Builds — Java/Node App
What & Why
Multi-stage builds use multiple FROM statements in one Dockerfile. Early stages compile/build; the final stage copies only the artifacts — keeping the production image small and secure.

Step-by-Step Hands-On Practice
Step 1 — Create the Project Structure
Run these commands to scaffold the project:

mkdir multi-stage-demo && cd multi-stage-demo
mkdir -p backend frontend

Step 2 — Create a Simple Java Backend (Spring Boot style)
<br>

backend/App.java (minimal, no framework needed for demo):public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        var server = com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer.create(
            new java.net.InetSocketAddress(8080), 0);
        server.createContext("/api", exchange -> {
            String response = "{\"message\": \"Hello from Java!\"}";
            exchange.sendResponseHeaders(200, response.length());
            exchange.getResponseBody().write(response.getBytes());
            exchange.getResponseBody().close();
        });
        server.start();
        System.out.println("Server started on port 8080");
    }
}

backend/build.sh:
javac App.java -d out/
jar cfe app.jar App -C out/ .

Step 3 — Create a Simple Node.js Frontend
frontend/package.json:
{
  "name": "frontend",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "scripts": { "build": "echo 'Building...' && mkdir -p dist && cp index.html dist/" },
  "devDependencies": {}
}

frontend/index.html:
  <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Multi-Stage Demo</h1>
    <script>
      fetch('/api').then(r => r.json()).then(d => document.body.innerHTML += `<p>${d.message}</p>`);
    </script>
  </body>
</html>

Step 4 — Write the Multi-Stage Dockerfile
Dockerfile (this is the core of the exercise):
# ─── Stage 1: Build Java Backend ─────────────────────────────────────────────
FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jdk AS java-builder

WORKDIR /app/backend
COPY backend/App.java .

# Compile and package
RUN mkdir -p out && \
    javac App.java -d out/ && \
    jar cfe app.jar App -C out/ .

# ─── Stage 2: Build Node.js Frontend ─────────────────────────────────────────
FROM node:20-alpine AS node-builder

WORKDIR /app/frontend
COPY frontend/package.json .

RUN npm install

COPY frontend/ .
RUN npm run build

# ─── Stage 3: Final Lean Production Image ─────────────────────────────────────
FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jre-alpine AS production

WORKDIR /app

# Copy ONLY the built artifacts from previous stages
COPY --from=java-builder  /app/backend/app.jar    ./app.jar
COPY --from=node-builder  /app/frontend/dist/      ./static/

EXPOSE 8080

# Non-root user for security
RUN addgroup -S appgroup && adduser -S appuser -G appgroup
USER appuser

ENTRYPOINT ["java", "-jar", "app.jar"]

Step 5 — Build and Compare Image Sizes
# Build the multi-stage image
docker build -t multi-stage-demo:latest .

# Compare sizes — notice the difference!
docker images | grep multi-stage-demo

# Build a naive single-stage for comparison
docker build --target java-builder -t naive-build:latest .
docker images | grep -E "multi-stage|naive-build"

Step 6 — Run and Test
docker run -d -p 8080:8080 --name demo multi-stage-demo:latest
curl http://localhost:8080/api
# Expected: {"message": "Hello from Java!"}

# Inspect what's inside the final image (no JDK, no node_modules!)
docker run --rm multi-stage-demo:latest sh -c "ls /app && java -version"

Step 7 — Advanced: Target a Specific Stage (for local dev)
# Run only the node-builder stage for frontend debugging
docker build --target node-builder -t frontend-dev:latest .
docker run --rm frontend-dev:latest ls /app/frontend/dist

Step 8 — Use BuildKit Cache Mounts (optimization)
# Replace the npm install line with:
RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.npm \
    npm install

# Enable BuildKit
DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1 docker build -t multi-stage-demo:latest .
# Second build will be MUCH faster

Interview Questions & Answers
Conceptual
Q1: What is a multi-stage build and why use it?

Multiple FROM instructions in one Dockerfile. Each stage can be named. Final stage copies only required artifacts. Benefits: smaller images, no build tools in production, better security posture.

Q2: What is the size difference you'd typically see?

A JDK image (500MB) + Node.js (350MB) single-stage vs a JRE-alpine final stage (~85MB). Easily 5-10x smaller in practice.

Q3: Are intermediate stage images cached?

Yes. Docker caches each stage layer independently. The cache is invalidated only when that stage's instructions or their inputs change.

Q4: How do you copy files between stages?

COPY --from=<stage-name-or-index> <src> <dest>. You can also copy from external images: COPY --from=nginx:alpine /etc/nginx/nginx.conf /etc/nginx/.

Q5: What happens to intermediate stages after a build?

They are discarded (not tagged) unless explicitly built with --target. Only final stage layers are in the resulting image.

Practical / Scenario-Based
Q6: How do you build only a specific stage?

docker build --target <stage-name> .

Q7: Can you run tests in a multi-stage build and fail the build if tests fail?

Yes. Add a test stage after the build stage, run tests there (RUN mvn test), then copy artifacts to final stage only if tests pass.
FROM maven:3.9 AS test
RUN mvn test   # Build fails here if tests fail

FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jre AS production
COPY --from=test /app/target/app.jar .
Q8: How do you pass build arguments across stages?

ARG is scoped per stage. Re-declare it in each stage that needs it:
ARG VERSION
FROM node:20 AS builder
ARG VERSION          # must re-declare
RUN echo $VERSION

Q9: What's the difference between ARG and ENV in multi-stage builds?

ARG is build-time only, not available at runtime, scoped per stage. ENV persists into the running container and all subsequent stages.

Q10: How can you speed up multi-stage builds in CI/CD?

Use --cache-from to pull cached layers from a registry
Use BuildKit with --mount=type=cache for package manager caches
Use docker buildx with inline cache: --build-arg BUILDKIT_INLINE_CACHE=1

Security-Focused
Q11: Why should the final stage use a non-root user?

If the container is compromised, the attacker has limited privileges. Use adduser + USER directive before ENTRYPOINT.

Q12: Why use -alpine or -slim base images in the final stage?

Smaller attack surface — fewer installed packages means fewer CVEs. Alpine uses musl libc and busybox, resulting in ~5MB base vs ~100MB Debian.

Q13: How do you ensure no secrets (API keys, build credentials) leak into the final image?

Use --mount=type=secret (BuildKit) instead of ENV or ARG for secrets
Secrets passed as ARG are visible in docker history — avoid this
Multi-stage naturally prevents build-time credentials from appearing in final stage layers

Debugging
Q14: How do you debug a failed intermediate stage?

Build up to that stage: docker build --target <failing-stage> . then docker run -it <image> sh

Q15: COPY --from fails with "stage not found" — why?

The stage name in FROM ... AS <name> must exactly match the name in --from=<name>. Names are case-insensitive but must exist in the same Dockerfile.

Quick Reference Cheatsheet
Concept	Command/Syntax
Name a stage	FROM image AS stagename
Copy from stage	COPY --from=stagename /src /dest
Copy from external image	COPY --from=nginx:alpine /etc/nginx .
Build specific stage	docker build --target stagename .
Enable BuildKit	DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1 docker build .
Cache mount	RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.m2 mvn package
Secret mount	RUN --mount=type=secret,id=mysecret cat /run/secrets/mysecret  
